<p>When comparing job offers, deciding between full-time employment and freelancing, or negotiating your pay rate, being able to convert between annual salary, monthly salary, and hourly rate is an essential skill. This guide covers all three conversions with Indian-specific examples and caveats.</p>

<h2>Why Convert Salary to Hourly?</h2>
<p>Converting your annual or monthly salary to an hourly rate helps you: compare a salaried job with a freelance/contract opportunity fairly, determine if you're being underpaid compared to market hourly rates, calculate the true opportunity cost of spending a day on non-billable activity, and negotiate with confidence in job interviews or client meetings.</p>

<h2>Formula: Annual Salary to Hourly Rate</h2>
<div style="background:#f4f6f8;padding:20px;border-left:5px solid #4f46e5;margin:20px 0;border-radius:8px;">
    <strong>Hourly Rate = Annual Salary / (Working Weeks Per Year × Work Hours Per Week)</strong><br><br>
    Standard: 52 weeks × 40 hours = 2,080 hours/year<br>
    India (less holidays): 50 weeks × 40 hours = 2,000 hours/year
</div>

<h2>Step-by-Step Example</h2>
<p>Annual CTC: ₹7,20,000 (₹60,000/month gross). Working 50 weeks × 40 hours = 2,000 hours/year.</p>
<ol>
    <li>Hourly Rate = ₹7,20,000 / 2,000 = <strong>₹360/hour</strong></li>
    <li>But take-home is ~₹50,000/month (after deductions) = ₹6,00,000/year</li>
    <li>Actual net hourly rate = ₹6,00,000 / 2,000 = <strong>₹300/hour</strong></li>
</ol>

<h2>Formula: Monthly Salary to Hourly Rate</h2>
<div style="background:#f4f6f8;padding:20px;border-left:5px solid #4f46e5;margin:20px 0;border-radius:8px;">
    <strong>Hourly Rate = Monthly Salary / (Working Days × Daily Work Hours)</strong>
</div>
<p>₹55,000/month. 22 working days/month. 8 hours/day.</p>
<p>Hourly Rate = ₹55,000 / (22 × 8) = ₹55,000 / 176 = <strong>₹312.50/hour</strong></p>

